import BaseLayout from "~/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---
<BaseLayout title="Method — Scarti" locale="en">
  <h1>Method</h1>
  <p class="report-lede">
    How Scarti decides whether a data point is unusual enough to warrant a report.
  </p>

  <h2>What we watch</h2>
  <p>
    Every Monday the pipeline pulls the last 60 months of the series listed in
    the repository catalog: prices, labour, production, confidence, credit. All sources are public and reached via official APIs —
    ISTAT, Bank of Italy, occasionally Eurostat.
  </p>

  <h2>How we detect anomalies</h2>
  <p>
    First we strip out seasonality (December always has more retail sales,
    August more tourists): if the source already publishes a seasonally
    adjusted version we use it, otherwise we apply an STL decomposition.
    On what remains — the residual — we compute where the last value sits
    against the median and the median absolute deviation (MAD) of the past
    five years.
  </p>
  <p>
    This is a robust ruler: an isolated past shock (think 2020 lockdowns)
    doesn't distort the scale. We flag a data point only when it sits more
    than two median deviations from typical — a bar you'd expect to cross
    by chance roughly once every two years if the series were actually flat.
  </p>

  <h2>What we don't do</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>We don't invent causal stories. A series that moves doesn't tell us
        <em>why</em> — only that it moved.</li>
    <li>We don't offer political or forward-looking economic judgements.</li>
    <li>We don't store or redistribute raw data: each week the pipeline
        re-fetches everything from the official source.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Transparency</h2>
  <p>
    The code is open source. Each report cites the SDMX dataflow of the
    monitored series so the detection can be reproduced.
  </p>
</BaseLayout>
